Experts and delegates at the year 2019 Digital Rights and Inclusion Forum (DRIF) have expressed concern over the spate of violation of human rights online on the African continent. The seventh edition of the forum organised by Paradigm Initiative with support from Google, Ford Foundation, and Heinrich Böll Stiftung is convened annually to provide platform where conversations on digital policy in Africa are shaped, and policy directions forged. In her submission at the Forum, which held in Lagos, the former Executive Director of the Association for Progressive Communications, Anriette Esterhuysen stressed the need for the internet to be protected and remain open; saying, it is the only means of expression for some minority groups to access information on issues that are not openly discussed. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. CLICK HERE TO KNOW MORE Also, speaking on the challenges facing efforts to improve internet penetration, the Chief Executive of MainOne Cable, Funke Opeke emphasised the need for government to partner the private sector instead of constituting itself as a stumbling block to expand internet access. Dr Ernest Ndukwe, a former chief executive of the Nigerian Communication Commission, also urged civil society and active citizens “to focus more attention on what government can do to ensure people have access.” Expert urges African media to embrace  digitalization Media Forum makes case for content development NCC boss wants right policies to fast track digital growth in Africa Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin